  "output": "## Codebase profile\n\nThis is a small (8-file) async Python job-scraper/pipeline, not a JS/React app — there's no `.tsx`/`.jsx` anywhere, so \"React re-renders\" doesn't apply here. I focused the other four categories on the actual stack: SQLite (`store.py`), `httpx`-based async fetchers (`fetchers.py`), and regex-based filtering (`filters.py`).\n\n## 1. N+1 query pattern — `Store.diff()` (store.py:55-74)\n\nEvery job triggers its own `SELECT` inside a Python loop:\n\n```python\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    ...\n```\n\nBoards like Microsoft/Amazon/Netflix paginate up to 40 pages × 10 = thousands of `Job`s per run (`fetchers.py:611,663,725`), so this is thousands of round-trip queries per pipeline run instead of one. Batch it into a single lookup:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n\n    keys = [j.key for j in jobs]\n    existing = {}\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), 900):  # stay under SQLite's ~999 param limit\n        chunk = keys[i:i + 900]\n        q = f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({','.join('?' * len(chunk))})\"\n        existing.update({r[\"key\"]: r[\"content_hash\"] for r in cur.execute(q, chunk)})\n\n    new, changed = [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        cached = existing.get(job.key)\n        if cached is None:\n            new.append(job)\n            self._insert(cur, job, now)\n        elif cached != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job)\n            self._update(cur, job, now)\n        else:\n            cur.execute(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", (now, job.key))\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nThis turns O(N) queries into O(N/900) + O(N) in-memory dict lookups.\n\n## 2. Redundant computation — regex recompiled per job (filters.py:11-26)\n\n`filter_jobs` calls `match()` once per job (filters.py:49), and `match()` calls `_compile(exclude)` / `_compile(include)` on *every single call* (filters.py:22,26) — recompiling the same keyword patterns from scratch for every job. For 5,000 jobs with 5 include + 5 exclude keywords, that's 50,000 `re.compile` calls for 10 distinct patterns.\n\nFix: compile once, outside the per-job loop.\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    cutoff = None\n    max_age = rules.get(\"max_age_days\")\n    if max_age:\n        cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=float(max_age))\n\n    include_re = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude_re = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    locations = rules.get(\"locations\")\n\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include_re, exclude=exclude_re,\n                                      locations=locations, cutoff=cutoff)]\n\n\ndef match(job: Job, *, include: list[re.Pattern] | None = None,\n          exclude: list[re.Pattern] | None = None,\n          locations: list[str] | None = None,\n          cutoff: datetime | None = None) -> bool:\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if exclude and any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude):\n        return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include):\n        return False\n    ...\n```\n\n(Update `match`'s type hints/signature to accept pre-compiled patterns rather than raw strings.)\n\n## 3. Redundant computation — `content_hash` computed twice for changed jobs (models.py:66-75)\n\n`Store.diff` reads `job.content_hash` once for the comparison (store.py:67), then `_update`/`_insert` call `job.to_row()`, which recomputes the same SHA-256 via `self.content_hash` again (models.py:75). Minor (one extra hash per changed/new job, not per job), but free to fix — compute once and pass it through:\n\n```python\ndef to_row(self, content_hash: str | None = None) -> dict[str, Any]:\n    d = asdict(self)\n    d.pop(\"raw\", None)\n    d[\"key\"] = self.key\n    d[\"content_hash\"] = content_hash if content_hash is not None else self.content_hash\n    return d\n```\nand pass the already-computed hash from `diff()` into `_insert`/`_update`.\n\n## 4. Memory — `Job.raw` is retained but never read (models.py:52, fetchers.py `raw=j`)\n\nEvery parser attaches the *entire original JSON record* to `Job.raw` (e.g. `parse_greenhouse`, `parse_lever`, etc. at fetchers.py:72,92,121...), but `grep -rn \"\\.raw\\b\"` across the repo shows it's only ever written, never read (`to_row()` immediately `d.pop(\"raw\", None)` at models.py:73). For a run pulling thousands of jobs from Amazon/Microsoft/Netflix, that's thousands of full upstream JSON payloads held in memory for the whole pipeline run for no reason.\n\nEither drop the field entirely, or make it opt-in/lazy if you expect to need it later for debugging:\n\n```python\nraw: dict[str, Any] = field(default=None, repr=False, compare=False)\n```\nand stop passing `raw=j` in every parser unless a `--debug-raw` flag is set. Simplest fix given it's unused: delete the field and every `raw=...` argument.\n\n## 5. Caching opportunity — none load-bearing found\n\nI did not find a good caching opportunity worth adding: the fetchers already do one HTTP round-trip per page with real dedup-by-`seen` pagination stops, `fetch_all` already runs sources concurrently under a semaphore (fetchers.py:767-788), and the SQLite connection/config are already loaded once per run. Introducing a cache here (e.g. across repeated `agent.py` invocations) would add staleness risk for a scraper whose whole purpose is freshness — not recommended.\n\n## Not applicable\n\n- **React re-renders**: no frontend code exists in this repo.\n- **Memory leaks**: none found — `httpx.AsyncClient` is closed in `fetch_all`'s `finally` (fetchers.py:785-787), `Store` uses a context manager (store.py:52-53), and the process is short-lived per invocation.\n\n**Priority**: fix #1 (N+1 SQL) first — it's the only issue with quadratic-ish wall-clock impact at current job volumes; #2 is next since it scales with source count × job count; #3 and #4 are cheap, low-risk cleanups.\n",
